hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider the upper half-space model of hyperbolic space $\mathbb{H}^{n}=\{(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}:x_{n}0\}$ equipped with the Riemannian metric $g$ given in coordinates by $g= rac{1}{x_{n}^{2}}\sum_{i=1}^{n}dx_{i}^{2}$, so that $g_{ij}(x)= rac{1}{x_{n}^{2}}\delta_{ij}$ and $g^{ij}(x)=x_{n}^{2}\delta^{ij}$. Starting from the defining properties of the Levi-Civita connection (torsion-free and metric-compatibility) and the coordinate expression for covariant differentiation, compute all Christoffel symbols $\Gamma^{k}_{ij}$ of $g$. Then, using only the definition of the Riemann curvature tensor $R(X,Y)Z=
abla_{X}
abla_{Y}Z-
abla_{Y}
abla_{X}Z-
abla_{[X,Y]}Z$ and the definition of sectional curvature of a $2$-plane $\sigma=\operatorname{span}\{X,Y\}$ with an orthonormal basis $\{X,Y\}$ as $K(\sigma)=g(R(X,Y)Y,X)$, verify that every sectional curvature of $g$ equals the same constant. Your final answer must be the value of that constant. Do not approximate; provide the exact value.
